comments.body:
@becarpenter 

> ...  the initial alert for a problem should come from a responsible person monitoring the list, and realistically that means a WG chair (or secretary, for WGs that appoint a secretary).

If the WG chairs could react this quick, we would not have an issue.  What I see is that it is other list members who alert people and it is when the WG chairs are not able to react quickly enough to those alerts that things can get bad quickly.

@sftcd I attempted to create a PR for this.  I looked at putting text into that paragraph, principles, and reorganizing the text above the example actions.

I failed for a few reasons:

1. We already mention fairness specifically in the principles;
2. The paragraph in question doesn't seem the correct place to try to reiterate one of or all of those principles;
3. I'm not really sure how to address the threat beyond the five safeguards that already exist.
4. I'm not sure what reference to add, even if I could find the right place.

If we are talking about a person from company X abusing their power against company Y, that is possible all over the place in the IETF, and I would argue it has in fact happened on occasion, and not just at the IETF. At least at the IETF it typically surfaces because everyone ends up yelling at the AD.  You may not have experienced this in the security area, but go ask the int and routing ADs.  So. my suggestion is to close this one, but perhaps you could otherwise create a PR?

@larseggert 

First, this isn't particularly about appeal.  Rather, it's about transparency.  14 days and everyone needs to know what happened.

But even if it were about appeals, we say that people should have the right to appeal moderator decisions.  So what's the problem?

```suggestion
- Disagreements about moderation actions are addressed through appeals;
```

@larseggert I think you replied to the wrong issue.

For this one, the suggested text in RFC 8174 should be used in "[1.3. ](https://larseggert.github.io/draft-ietf-modpod-group-processes/draft-ietf-modpod-group-processes.html#section-1.3)[Conventions and Definitions](https://larseggert.github.io/draft-ietf-modpod-group-processes/draft-ietf-modpod-group-processes.html#name-conventions-and-definitions)"

https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8174

```suggestion
# Non-Normative Examples of Disruptive Behavior {#examples}
```

```suggestion
  without regard to one's role in the IETF or previous technical contributions;
```
